column168: According to the information obtained the following occurred.  While unloading at the consignee's location, one leaking, 5-gallon plastic pail was discovered in the trailer. The material safety data sheet was requested and received.

column168: The driver of the crude oil transport had loaded approximately 20 barrels of oil from the producer's tank when he decided not to purchase the load of oil, because it did not meet minimum requirements.  The driver reversed his pump, pumping oil back into the producer's tank.  When the tanker was empty, the pump blew air into the bottom of the tank causing oil to flow out the top hatch on the tank.  The driver contacted his supervisor immediately.  After evaluating the situation, the driver was instructed to measure how much oil was left in the tank after the incident versus how much was in the tank when he began to load the oil.  An estimated 1.68 barrels of oil had flown out of the top of the tank onto the ground and down the side of the tank.  The supervisor contacted a vacuum truck and a steamer truck to meet him at the location.  The vacuum truck was instructed to suck up as much oil off the top of the ground as possible.  The steamer truck was then asked to wash the sides of the tank off, and wash down the affected dike area.  While the water was flowing down the same path that the oil had taken, the vacuum truck was vacuuming all of the water and oil thas had flowed down the slope.  After the steamer truck was excused from the location, the vacuum hose was walked to each puddle of water and vacuumed onto the truck.  The supervisor covered the spill with sphag absorbent after the vacuum truck had the water puddles all drained.
column169: The  area truck supervisor has left a message to all of the drivers in his area about how this incident happened and how to prevent this from happening again.  The driver will be re-instructed on how to load and unload oil onto the tanker trailer.  He will also be re-instructed on how to pump oil back into a producer's tank.  The driver will have a meeting with the area truck supervisor, district supervisor, and regional supervisor to discuss the incident and how this could have been prevented. This matter will be covered with all of the crude drivers in the upcoming safety meetings.

column168: Pasenger had checked in a small bag containing between 15 and 20 plastic water bottles. Most of the bottles were still labeled and sealed however there were seven bottles that were unlabled containing a yellowish liquid that smelled of alcohol. One of the bottles had opened spilling its contents into the bag and giving it an overpowering smell of alcohol. It was in this state that the bag was found by TSA screeners. Upon opening of the bag it was found that the inside of the bag was wet and that there were bottles containing something other than the contents on the label. All seven bottles were collected and disposed of as if they were haz mat as there was no one able to verify their contents other than the smell they emited. The suitcase was placed inside of a large plastic bag in case any of the alcohol leaked through to the outside and was sent on to MIA with only the unopened and labeled water bottles inside.
column169: Passengers need to be made aware that only certain amounts of alcohol are allowed in checked or carry on luggage.
column172: Plastic bottle, capacity 2 gallons or less

column168: Material was being unloaded from trailer D/SR noticed a small amount of material leaking from bungs on drums. Material was contained in the HazMat OS&D area. Contact was made with Safety Manager. Shippers Emergency Response Number was called for disposition. Per conversation with CircleProsco Inc. Seals were removed from drums absorbent material was used to soak up residue and placed in a small salvage drum along with gloves used in clean up procedure. Bungs were tightened and leakage was stopped. Shipment is continuing movement to destination for delivery.

column168: An employee was loading several pallets containing stacked and shrink-wrapped 5 gallon steel pails (36 per pallet) of lacquer thinner onto a van trailer for shipment. While attempting to pickup one of the pallets from the dock to move to the truck, one of the cans on the pallet was punctured by the blade on the forklift creating a hole in the side of the pail that was about 3" by 1". This allowed approximately 1 1/2 gallons of the material to leak out onto the concrete floor of the loading dock. The spilled material was properly cleaned up and disposed of by our operations personnel.
column169: Affected employee was retrained and recertified on forklift operation. Incident was used as a tailgate meeting topic with other employees to raise safety awareness.

column168: OUR CARGO TANK MOTOR VEHICLE WAS TRAVELING EAST BOUND ON U.S. HIGHWAY 40. THE DRIVER SAW AN ELK IN THE ROADWAY BUT COULD NOT STOP IN TIME TO AVOID COLLIDING WITH ONE OF THEM. column168: A PUNCTURE IN THE PLUMBING LEADING TO THE TRANSFER PUMP WAS THE CAUSE OF THE SPILL. IT IS LIKELY THAT ROAD HAZARD CAUSED THE PUNCTURE.  BECAUSE OF THE LOCATION OF THE PUNCTURE, IT WAS NOT VISIBLE TO THE DRIVER PRIOR TO ENGAGING THE TRANSFER PUMP.  WHEN THE PUMP WAS ENGAGED THE PRODUCT WAS SUBJECTED TO PRESSURE AND APPROXIMATELY 150 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL WAS SPILLED BEFORE ALL VALVES COULD BE SHUT DOWN.    OUR EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM QUICKLY ARRIVED AT THE LOCATION AND SPREAD CLAY ABSORBENTS ON THE ENTIRE SPILL.  NO PRODUCT ENTERED ANY WATER DRAINS OR CONTACTED ANY SOIL SINCE THE ENTIRE SURFACE WAS CONCRETE AND ASPHALT.    THE ABSORBENT MATERIALS WERE COLLECTED AND WILL BE DISPOSED OF ACCORDING TO ALL APPLICABLE REGULATIONS.

The tank tank was an empty with residue last contained UN3266.  It wa0s loaded on board the ocean vessel when it was noticed dripping from the discharge valve flange gasket.  It was removed from the vessel and the emergency response contractor and the local fire departments responded to the small spill.  It was determined that the spill was caused by the loose bolts securing the discharge valve to the tank shell.  The bolts were secured and the shipper notified of the spill.  The response contractor cleaned up the small spill on the vessel and the marine terminal.
column169: This tank should have been inspected by the shipper prior to tendering the equipment to the ocean vessel carrier.

CSXT HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO REPAIR THE SOURCE OF THE RELEASE. THE CONTRACTOR REPORTED THAT THE MANWAY COVER GASKET WAS NOT PROPERLY SEATED AND ALL 6 MANWAY COVER SECUREMENT BOLTS WERE ONLY HAND TIGHT. column168: The container which the vehicle was loaded in was received and stowed to the vessel.  We received notification from the shipper that they had failed to declare the vehicle.  They forwarded corrected documentation.  We advised the vessel and the destination terminal.  The shipper failed to include the vehicle on his bill of lading.
column169: The shipper should take the time to verify all the cargo loaded within a container.  There should also be a requirement for the cargo to arrive the marine terminal 24 hours prior prior to the anticipated lifting to the vessel.  This will allow shipper and carrier the time to properly handle the hazardous cargo.

column168: The shipment had been received and loaded to the vessel when the shipper provided a dangerous goods declaration indicating that the bulk cargo tank was hazardous.  It was and empty listed as RQ, Residue, Last Contained.  The manifest was updated, the vessel master notified along with the destination terminal.
column169: There need to be more time for the shipper and carrier to reconcile documentation prior to the vessel arrival and loading.  There should be a 24 hour requirement for the cargo to be in the terminal prior to loading to the cargo vessel.

column168: I WAS CALLED TO THE FIFE OFFICE WHERE I WAS TOLD THAT A DRIVER HAD A LEAKING HAZMAT PACKAGE ON HER TRUCK. I WAS INFORMED THAT THE HAZMAT WAS A RED SUBSTANCE THAT HAD A DIAMOND LABEL WITH THE NUMBER 9. SO I WENT AND I GOT ALL MY PPE(GLOVES, BOOTS, GOGGLES,APRON) AND I ALSO GOT MY BOX KNIFE, PH TAPE AND I ALSO GRABBED MY DECISION TREE. I THEN PROCEEDED TO GO TO FORT LEWIS TO PICK UP THE LEAKING HAZMAT. I THEN DON'D MY PPE AND PROCEEDED TO THE HAZMAT. I TRIED TO PH TEST IT BUT WAS UNABLE TO GET A READING BECAUSE THE SUBSTANCE WAS RED. SO I THEN SPRINKLED SOME CLAY ABSORBENT INTO THE SPILL TRAY AND THEN I PLACED THE LEAKING HAZMAT INTO IT.I THEN SPRINKED SOME CLAY ABSORBENT ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE TRUCK AND THEN CLEANED IT UP. I THEN BROUGHT THE LEAKING HAZMAT BACK TO THE CENTER WHERE I PROCESSED IT THROUGH THE DMP.

column168: Driver stopped in route to destination, discovered material leaking through trailer floor.  Investigated and found that material was leaking within the load.  Put down plastic sheeting to contain leaking material.  Forced absorbant materials between drums to contain leak.  ER contractor called to scene to facilitate response.  Other containers were unloaded onto another carrier vehicle dispatched to the scene.  Leaking drum was located, and overpacked in specification container.  Loose bolt was found on floor of trailer.  Floor of trailer was cleaned, absorbant materials contained in overpack.  Shipment was returned to shipping facility for inspection and reload.  Loose bolt from trailer was found to perfectly match profile of container puncture.  Other than evaporative loss and the trailer interior, there was no release at the scene of the response.
column169: Apparent cause of failure was the puncture of the container by a loose object on the floor of the trailer.  Recommended procedural changes will include inspection of trailer floors and walls for loose and fixed/protruding objects that could potentially damage packages, and removal or correction prior to loading.

column168: Driver arrived at the consignee’s location with a 330 gallon intermediate bulk container of 12.5% sodium hypochlorite solution. He positioned his vehicle in the unloading area, prepared his equipment, and donned his personnel protective equipment. He verified that the unloading valve handle was in the proper “closed“ position.  Upon removing the external cap, material began to flow out of the container. Approximately 50 gallons of a 12.5% sodium hypochlorite solution was released in the unloading area on to a concrete surface.  The driver was able to replace the external cap and stop the flow. The valve orientation was rechecked and the external cap secured in place.   The incident was reported to customer representatives who cleaned up the affected area.

column168: Veolia ES Technical Solutions was transporting a bulk tanker shipment of waste toluene diamine from Air Products for disposal.  Prior to shipment, the Veolia driver performed a vehicle inspection that included the tanker trailer and valve on the trailer.  All required vehicle inspections and registrations were current.  Nothing was identified as inoperable or improper for shipment.  The trailer was being leased to Air Products from Southern Tank Leasing Company.  Veolia transported the shipment approximately 10 miles from the shipper when the driver was alerted to a drip escaping from the rear valve of the tanker trailer.  A plastic bucket and inorganic absorbent was used initially to contain the material.  The National Response Center, City of La Porte police, and City of LA Porte fire department were immediately contacted.  Hazardous materials emergency responders were contacted and arrived within one hour of the initial identification of the release.  Responders containerized all the spilled materials and shipped it off-site for proper disposal.  The drip from the tanker truck was stopped and temporarily blocked.  The tanker was returned with a police escort to the shipper within 3 hours of the initial release incident.  Further investigation by Air Products into the leased  tanker truck found that some bolts inside the tanker related to the valve were not tightened sufficiently.
column169: Shippers who lease tanker trucks must not only verify that proper inspections and registrations are current for the equipment, but must verify that all valves and bolts related to these valves are tightened properly prior to loading.

THE OPERATOR DID NOT HAVE THIS LINE (HOSE) PROPERLY INSTALLED IN THE R/C SO THIS 150 GALLONS OF ALCOHOL AND 427.5 OUNCES OF BROCINE SULFATE WENT TO/ON THE GROUND.    IT WAS ABSORBED USING DRY RATTLE FEED, EXCEPT FOR AN ESTIMATED 50 GALLONS WHICH WENT TO OUR INTERNAL WASTE WATER TREATMENT PLANT. column168: Waste corrovive liquid was loaded onto a ROMIC cargo tanker and sealed by ROMIC driver. The tanker was then driven from shipper site to ROMIC (designated facility). At or about one mile (1) mile from shipper site waste corrosive mixture reacted with a residual material in the tanker remaining from previous shipment. The reaction of the corrosive mixture with residual material created a vapor gas dispersion release from the tanker dome hatch. The ROMIC driver pulled the tanker to the side of the road and local fire department responded. The tanker was observed for several hours until reaction ceased and the tanker was returned to the shipper and placed over secondary containment. During close examination it was determined that four securing bolts on the dome hatch were loose by one-quarter to one-half turn that may have allowed for the release of vapor. The tanker was fully inspected, dome hatch re-secured, exterior cleaned, and then shipped to ROMIC on January 18th, 2007 without further incident.
column169: ROMIC is conducting the following actions to prevent future incidents. (1)Review and amend as warrented hazardous material transportation SOP specific to cargo tank clean out and pre-loading procedures. (2) Enhanced facility and driver employee training specific to bulk hazardous material and packaging compatibilities and chemical compatabilities common to materials recieved by ROMIC. (3) Review and amend as warrented current ROMIC SOP for ER and ER notification procedures for ROMIC employees and subcontractors. (3) Review and amend and/or develop new sepcific shipper/ROMIC SOP for hazardous material loading requirements. (4) Conduct enhanced facility management and employee training pretaining to DOT performance standards.

At approximately 7:00 AM on 01/15/07 a leaking container was discovered at Clean Harbors in-transit storage facility located at 32 Tompkins Pint Road, Newark, NJ.  Please note that at the time of the release the container was stored in a fully contained section of a concrete floor warehouse.  Upon noticing the release, the warehouse supervisor retrieved the shipping papers for all of the materials stored in the warehouse, evacuated the immediate area, and notified his operations manager.    An in house response crew was dispatched to assess the situation.  Utilizing the appropriate personal protection equipment, and company health and safety procedures, the emergency response personnel entered the warehouse in order to identify the material involved.  Upon reviewing the material markings and labels, it was determined that the material involved was a shipment of hazardous waste flammable liquid, n.o.s. (xylene, toluene) 3, UN1993, PGII picked up from Hovione on 01/11/07 on EPA hazardous waste manifest 000600395FLE.  It was also determined that out of 29 drums shipped one drum had developed a pin-hole in the bottom seam and released about 10 gallons of material.  One additional drum appeared to have developed internal pressure and was beginning to bulge; however, no container failure occurred.  The response crew personnel utilized a pH indicator paper to screen the spilled material for any potential corrosivity.  They determined that the spilled material showed acidic properties.  The generator (Hovione) was contacted to inform them that there was an incident involving their waste shipment and that the spilled material was showing corrosive characteristics not disclosed in the shipping papers.  Although the internal investigation is still ongoing, Hovione was able to identify that there was an error during the preparation of waste material for shipment and that two of the drums containing small amount of Hydrochloric Acid were inadvertently grouped with the remaining 27 drums as being the same.  One of the drums that contained Hydrochloric Acid was the drum that had failed, and the other drum was the drum that was beginning to bulge.    The two drums in question were placed into appropriate salvage drums, all of the released material was cleaned up using an appropriate absorbent and placed into suitable shipping container for disposal at a fully permitted hazardous waste disposal facility.  Additionally, the shipping names for the two containers were changed to Waste Flammable Liquid, Corrosive n.o.s. (methanol, hydrochloric acid) 3(8), UN2924, PGII to reflect the corrosivity of the material.  The in-house clean up crew completed the clean up operations without any incidents and no off-site impact occurred.
column169: Because this waste stream contained Hydrochloric Acid, it should not have been placed into steel containers.  Although, at times steel containers are authorized for acidic materials, they are susceptible to corrosion from low pH.  It is Clean Harbor’s policy not to transport acidic materials in steel container.  Additionally, the generator of this waste needs to complete a full investigation to determine how acidic material ended up in the drums and how it was allowed to ship without being properly identified.  Additionally Clean Harbor’s employees involved with this shipment will be reminded to perform a thorough drum inspection prior to placing the containers in transit.  They will be reminded to look for signs of corrosion, pressurization, or weakening of seams and chimes.

column168: On Saturday, January 20th at 1100 hours, CSX Transportation’s Bennett Yard. Car Inspector, observed Tank Car D0DX14357 (Residue -. Last Contained Fuel, Aviation, Turbine Engine) dripping product from the bottom outlet valve area. CSX Management immediately implemented their emergency action plan and the rail car was isolated, The shipper, US Government was contacted and informed of the release. CSX contracted Hepaco Environmental to respond and secure the container. Once on site, Hepaco representatives found the cause of the release was due to the following: bottom outlet valve open (operating handle in open position - not pinned), bottom outlet cap less than tool tight, and bottom outlet cap gasket deteriorated. Approximately two gallons of product was released onto the ballast media. At 1420 hours, Hepaco properly secured the container and the rail car was released to destination.    Cause Code: 148  NARRI: 5 (4+1+0) x (2+0) = 50

BNSF YARD PERSONNEL REPORTED DOWX 49074 LEAKING PRODUCT IN THE RAILYARD. A BNSF MECHANICAL/HAZARDOUS MATERIAL RESPONDER INSPECTED DOWX 49074. SEAL 200888 WAS REMOVED FROM THE VALVE PROTECTIVE HOUSING COVER. RESPONDER FOUND THE SOURCE OF LEAK AT THE LIQUID VALVE’S VALVE HANDLE STEM. THE VALVE STEM RETAINER NUT WAS TOOL TIGHTENED FROM 1/4 TO 1/2 TURN, WHICH ENDED THE PRODUCT RELEASE BY 1045 HRS. CST, 1/11/07. A SMALL OF AMOUNT OF SPILLAGE THAT DID NOT EVAPORATE NEAR THE VALVE FLANGES WAS WIPED. THE RESPONDER CONTINUED TO MONITOR DOWX 49074 FOR ANY FURTHER SIGNS OF PRODUCT LEAKAGE. AFTER NO FURTHER PRODUCT LEAKAGE WAS OBSERVED, THE VALVE PROTECTIVE HOUSING COVER WAS CLOSED AND RESEALED WITH BNSF 002408 NUMBERED SEAL. NO GROUND IMPACT FROM THIS PRODUCT RELEASE WAS EVIDENT.

A BNSF INBOUND TRAIN INSPECTION IN THE RAILYARD BY BNSF RAILCAR INSPECTORS REVEALED GATX 80578 LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE TOP OF THIS TANK CAR. BNSF MECHANICAL/HAZARDOUS MATERIAL RESPONDERS REMOVED THE SEAL FROM THE VALVE PROTECTIVE HOUSING COVER TO ASCERTAIN THE LEAK SOURCE. RESPONDERS REDUCED THE INTERNAL PRESSURE IN GATX 80578 AND TOOL TIGHTENED THE RETAINER NUT, ENDING FURTHER PRODUCT RELEASE BY 1715 HRS. PST, 1/26/07. BNSF SEAL NUMBERED 06157821 WAS APPLIED TO VALVE HOUSING COVER. ALL SPILLAGE EVAPORATED AND NO GROUND IMPACT WAS EVIDENT.

column168: Freight was shipped in 7 55 gal drums.  These were shrink wrapped ontp pallets.  Shipment was loaded in the nose of trailer 84201.  Chris Carper (employee who stripped trailer) noticed a faint odor while working, but really did not think much of it.  By the time we got to the nose of the trailer he   was feeling a burning sensation to his face and neck and was having difficulty breathing.  A couple of the drums had slid partially off the pallets.  Looks like the plugs on top of the drums had a vent that was slightly leaking when the drums were moved or vibrated.  We sat the shipment in the yard   on the trailer and the residue dried up and odor disappeared.  We will attempt to deliver this shipment tomorrow.~~Dock worker Chris Carper did go to the doctor and missed the remaining 5 hours of his shift that day. He was released and returned to work the next day. He was not prescribed any type of medication. The type of injury would be classified as a respiratory irritation.
column169: Shipper needs to be notified about possible faulty plugs screwing in the to the top of these drums.  Drums have to be better secured in trailer to prevent in movement during transit.

column25: WASHINGTON STATE UNIVERSITY TREE FRUIT RESEARCH
column168: A 55 GALLON (1G/X143/S/06/USA/GBC) CONTAINER PACKAGED IN ACCORDANCE WITH 49CFR, PART 173.12 AS A “LAB PACK” WAS BEING TRANSFERRED FROM ONE TRUCK TO ANOTHER AT A 10-DAY TRANSFER FACILITY OPERATED IN ACCORDANCE WITH 40 CFR, PART 263.12, AT THE TIME OF THE OCCURANCE, THE CONTAINER IN QUESTION WAS BEING PLACED ON A PALLET TO FACILITATE THE TRANSFER. AS THE CONTAINER WAS MOVED ONTO THE PALLET, THE BOTTOM OF THE CONTAINER WAS PUNCTURED BY THE CORNER OF THE WOOD PALLET CAUSING A SMALL CONTAINER OF MERCURY TO BREAK, ALLOWING APPROXIMATELY ONE (1) OUNCE OF METALLIC MERCURY TO ESCAPE FROM THE CONTAINER ONTO A CONCRETE LOADING DOCK.     THE TRANSFER OPERATION WAS IMMEDIATELY SUSPENDED AND A RESPONSE CREW INITIATED THE CLEAN-UP USING A MERCURY DECONTAMINATION AND CLEAN-UP KIT. ALL MERCURY WAS RECOVERED AND THE CLEAN-UP DEBRIS, ALONG WITH THE COMPROMISED CONTAINER, WAS PLACED INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM AND TRANSPORTED TO THE INTENDED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY.     THERE WERE NO OFF-SITE IMPACTS ASSOCIATED WITH THIS EVENT.
column169: IN ORDER TO PREVENT A REOCURRENCE, WAREHOUSE PERSONNEL HAVE BEEN RE-INSTRUCTED TO FOLLOW ALL LOADING PROCEDURES AND ARE TO USE MECHANICAL LOADING DEVICES WHENEVER POSSIBLE. IN ADDITION; PRIOR TO UTILIZING A PALLET, IT IS TO BE INSPECTED TO INSURE THAT THERE ARE NO RAISED NAILS OR PIECES OF WOOD THAT COULD CONTRIBUTE TO A PUNCTURE OF A CONTAINER BEING PLACED UPON IT.

While making deliveries, a loaded tractor trailer overturned north of Haskell, TX on Highway 277 losing its load of cylinders and drums.  DPC personnel notified the NRC and TCEQ Region 3 office.  Eagle Construction & Environmental Services was contacted to aid in clean-up.   All cylinders and drums were recovered and returned to the Sweetwater facility.  It was determined that 4-lbs of chlorine and 405-gals of sodium hypochlorite was lost.  Eagle collected approximately 20-yards of contaminated soil for disposal.

column168: On January 11, 2007, at approximately 0700 hours, a railway tankcar ARIX 43114, loaded with Carbon Dioxide, Refrigerated Liquid, nonflammable gas, UN2187, was reported venting at the Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) Shreveport Louisiana yard. The tank car was discovered leaking from a ruptured frangible disk. The shipper representative responded to the site and replaced the disk. There were no injuries, no damage to the environment. column169: On The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR), shippers are immediately notified of all HAZMAT releases. For non-accident releases (a.k.a. package or closure defects), where possible, shippers (responsible party) are requested to respond, repair and remediate. By immediately involving the shipper, in-depth knowledge of the release cause is gained by the same organization that can implement process changes to prevent recurrence. After each NAR incident, KCSR provides outreach to the shipper to help investigate root-cause factors for correction. For non-accident related releases, the shipper should be contacted directly for details associated with actions taken to prevent recurrence.

column168: AFTER GETTING FUEL AT BIG Z TRAVEL PLAZA, OUR DRIVER DROVE OFF ON AN ACCESS ROAD. THE DRIVER THEN REMEMBERED THAT HE HADN’T PAID FOR FUEL. HE THEN WENT BACK TO BIG Z TRAVEL PLAZA. AS HE STEPPED OUT OF HIS TRUCK, HE NOTICED THAT THE TOTE TANK OF METHANOL WAS LEAKING. HE CLIMBED INTO THE BACK OF THE TRUCK TO MAKE SURE THE VALVE WAS CLOSED. AS HE PLACED HIS HAND ONTO THE VALVE IT BROKE OFF BETWEEN THE VALVE AND THE MAIN BODY LEAVING A 2-INCH HOLE AND EMPTYING 230 GALLONS OF METHANOL ONTO THE DRIVE OF BIG Z TRAVEL PLAZA. THIS TOOK PLACE IN LESS THAN 5 MINUTES FROM BROKEN TO EMPTY. THE DRIVER CONTACTED HIS SUPERVISOR AND HIS SUPERVISOR CONTACTED GARNER ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL. RHOME, TX FIRE DEPARTMENT BARRICADED AND EVACUATED THE TRAVEL PLAZA, WHILE GARNER ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES MITIGATED THE SPILL UNDER THE SUPERVISION OF THE RHOME FIRE DEPARTMENT. SEVEN HOURS PASSED FROM THE TIME OF SPILL UNTIL THE TIME CLEAN UP WAS DONE. THIS TOOK PLACE IN 25 DEGREE F WEATHER CONTRIBUTING TO VALVE BREAKING ALONG WITH THE WEIGHT OF THE HOSE HOOKED TO THE VALVE IN TRANSIT.
column169: 1. UNHOOK ALL HOSES BEFORE MOVING THE TRUCK.   2. MAINTAIN SECURITY OF TOTE TANKS TO STOP MOVEMENT IN TRANSIT.   3. PERIODIC VALVE REPLACEMENT ON TOTE TANKS.   4. UPDATE AND REVIEW JOB SAFETY ANALYSIS (JSAs)   5. REVIEW DOT EXEMPTION 12412.   6. UPDATE EMERGENCY CALL LIST.   7. DRIVER TRAINING ON OPERATION OF DELIVERY TRUCKS.   8. DISCUSS SPILL PREVENTION.

On January 19, 2007 at 1300 hours, loading Operator set up to load a Durpee trailer (#27022) with styrene. Loading arm was put inside of trailer. Arm was secured, but loose. When Operator started loading, the loading arm backed out and the styrene spilled to the secondary containment at the truck loading area. Operator immediately shutdown the loading and secured the loading arm. Release lasted 30 seconds. The loading area was flushed with water into the process drain to be re-processed.
column169: The Operator was required to review loading procedures.  The Operator was instructed to secure the loading arm more tightly to prevent movement. Reviewed Loading/Unloading Procedure with all Operating personnel.

I CLIMBED ON TOP OF THE FREIGHT BECAUSE WE SAW THAT ONE OF THE HAZ-MAT BOXES WAS CRUSHED UNDERNEATH SOME FREIGHT THAT SLID FORWARD DURING TRANSIT. I SAW A COUPLE OF DROPS OF WHAT LOOKED LIKE AN ADHESIVE TYPE SUBSTANCE ON THE PALLET. WE OPENED UP THE CARTON AND FOUND SEVERAL OF THE 8 OZ. CANISTERS CRUSHED AND LEAKING. WE PLACED THE LEAKING CANISTERS (NOW DRIED OUT SINCE IT WAS AN ADHESIVE) IN A SALVAGE DRUM AND PLACED THE GOOD ONES IN ANOTHER BOX SO IT COULD BE LOADED TO DENVER. I WOULD ESTIMATE THE DURATION OF THE LEAKAGE TO BE AROUND 36 HOURS.
column169: EMPLOYEE WHO LOADED THIS SHIPMENT NEEDS TO BE RE-TRAINED ON HOW TO PROPERLY BLOCK AND BRACE THE FREIGHT TO MINIMIZE DAMAGES. IT IS NOT CONWAY POLICY TO LOAD HAZARDOUS MATERIAL ON TOP OF ANY FREIGHT OR ON TOP OF LOAD RACKS.

column168: THERE WAS NO RELEASE ASSOCIATED WITH THIS INCIDENT.  OUR LITTLE ROCK LOCATION WAS RECEIVING A STATION AUDIT OF ITS PARTS INVENTORY.  THIS PARTICULAR ITEM WAS NOTED AS AN OVERSTOCKED ITEM AND WAS ABOUT TO EXCEED ITS' SHELF LIFE.  THE ITEM WAS SHIPPED TO DALLAS STORES LOCATION AS COMAT.  THIS ITEM WAS NOT MARKED AS HAZMAT BECAUSE IT WAS A PART THAT WAS RECEIVED PRIOR TO JANUARY 2005.  ALL INVENTORY RECEIVED AFTER JANUARY 2005 HAS BEEN LABELED WITH **HAZMAT** ON EACH ITEM, IF IT IS IN FACT A REGULATED ITEM.
column169: ALL SOUTHWEST AIRLINES PARTS FACILTIES AND STORES LOCATIONS WILL BE NOTIFIED OF THIS OCCURANCE.  AS PREVIOUSLY MENTIONED, WE HAD PRINTED LABELS AS OF JANUARY 2005 TO PREVENT THIS FROM HAPPENING.  HOWEVER, ONE OF THE BATTERIES THAT WAS ALREADY IN STOCK DID NOT GET THE NEW LABEL.  WE WILL MAKE SURE ALL EXISTING STOCK ITEMS WILL BE CHECKED FOR THIS LABEL.  WE ARE ALSO LOOKING AT EACH FACILITY PLACING A MORE NOTICEABLE LABEL ON THE REGULATED ITEMS IN STOCK AND ANY NEW ITEMS.  WE WILL ALSO MAKE SURE OUR STATION AUDIT SHEETS AN OUR INVENTORY SHEETS ARE NOTED AS HAZMAT FOR THOSE PARTICULAR ITEMS.

ALL SPILLED MATERIAL AND THE SURROUNDING AREA WAS CLEANED UP BY AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR CONTRACTED BY HAZMAT ENVIRONMENTAL GROUP, INC.  ALL SPILLED MATERIAL AND CLEANUP DEBRIS WAS PLACED IN A 30-GALLON FIBER CONTAINER AND REMAINED AT THE FACILITY FOR DISPOSAL.
column169: DETAILS OF THIS INCIDENT HAVE BEEN SHARED WITH ALL EMPLOYEES OF HAZMAT ENVIRONMENTAL GROUP, INC.  IN ADDITION, INCIDENT DETAILS HAVE BEEN INCORPORATED INTO HAZMAT'S 8-HOUR ANNUAL REFRESHER TRAINING FOR DRIVERS, WHICH IS CURRENTLY IN PROGRESS.  EMPHASIS IS BEING STRESSED ON THE CORRECT PROCEDURES FOR SAMPLING AND PRESSURIZING TRAILERS AS WELL AS THE IMPORTANCE OF THE PROPER USE OF PPE.

column168: AIRCRAFT ARRIVED IN HOLL AT APPROX. 2220 HRS. LOCAL TIME.  RAMP AGENTS NOTICED NOTHING UNUSUAL AT TIME OF DOWNLOAD.  WHEN THE AGENTS WERE UNLOADING THE CART AT THE CARGO FACILITY, THEY NOTICED THE BOX WAS LEAKING.  THE BOX WAS MOVED TO THE FLOOR AND INSPECTED.  UPON OPENING THE BOX, A STRONG ODOR WAS PRESENT.  CONTENTS IN THE BOX WERE WET AND WAS LEAKING FROM A PLASTIC BOTTLE LABELED HYDROCLORIC ACID (HCL-6N).  IT SMELLED TO BE A MIXTURE WITH URINE.  DURING INSPECTION, THE PRIMARY RECEPTACLE WAS NOT PACKED IN SECONDARY PACKAGING AND OBVIOUSLY, THERE WAS NO ABSORBANT MATERIAL EITHER.  SEE CONT. PAGE.    THE SOUTHWEST CARGO SUPERVISOR CONTACTED THE 3E COMPANY AND INQUIRED ABOUT MEDICAL AND EXPOSURE PRECAUTIONS.  THE SHIPPING COMPANY (QUEST DIAGNOSTICS) WAS ALSO CONTACTED TO INQUIRE ABOUT THE ACID CONCENTRATION IN THE BOTTLE.  DUE TO THE CORROSIVE NATURE OF HCL, THE CARGO SUPERVISOR ALSO CONTACTED MAINTENANCE.  MAINTENANCE CLEANED THE AIRCRAFT BIN WITH A NEUTRALIZING AGENT AS A PRECAUTION.    A QUEST REPRESENTATIVE WAS BROUGHT OVER FROM THE DOCK AREA TO LOOK AT THE BOX AND PACKAGING.  HE COULDN'T BELIEVE THE PACKAGE WAS PACKED THE WAY IT WAS.  HE, TOOK CONTROL OF THE PACKAGE AT THAT TIME.    THE HCL APPEARS TO BE A STABALIZING SOLUTION USED TO TREAT THE URINE SPECIMEN.     THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED.

A leaking drum was discovered during off loading/receipt of trailer at the Veolia facility in Creedmoor, NC. Upon investigation, it was determined that a 55-gallon steel drum was leaking from the side of the container. The spilled material was absorbed with speedy dri and the faulty drum was placed in a Salvage Drum.
column169: The driver was instructed to inspect drums in greater detail while at a customer's site and prior to loading onto truck.  Any questionable containers must be overpacked into in a suitable container. This incident was and will be used as an example during training exercises this year.

column168: A small leak was discovered during a daily inspection of Veolia's 10-day transfer facility located in Morrow, GA.  Upon further investigation, it was determined that a 55-gallon steel drum had leaked a small amount of flammable liquid due to overfilling.  The spill was localized to the top of the container.  The leaking container was overpacked into a salvage drum and delivered to the ultimate disposal site.

column168: DURING SWITCHING OPERATIONS IN THE RAILYARD, A BNSF EMPLOYEE WAS SPLASHED BY PRODUCT DROPLETS EMANATING FROM PROX 15127 WHEN A COUPLING JOINT WAS MADE. THE EMPLOYEE STANDING ON THE GROUND APPROXIMATELY 20-25 FEET AWAY FROM PROX 15127, TURNED AWAY FROM THE FLYING DROPLETS WHICH LANDED ON THE RIGHT SIDE OF EMPLOYEE’S CLOTHING AND FACIAL AREA (CHEEK AND BEHIND THE EAR). THE EMPLOYEE WAS DECONTAMINATED AND EXAMINED AT A LOCAL MEDICAL CENTER. MEDICAL FIRST AID AND PRESCRIPTIONS OF PAIN AND BURN RELIEF WERE ADMINISTERED. THIS EMPLOYEE DID NOT LOSE ANY WORKDAYS. PROX 15127 WAS CORDONED OFF IN THE RAILYARD AND PLASTIC SHEETING WAS PLACED UNDER THIS TANK CAR. BNSF AND CONTRACT RESPONDERS INSPECTED PROX 15127 AND FOUND THAT THE THREE FILL HOLE COVER SECUREMENT BOLTS WERE NOT TOOL TIGHT BY 2 1/2 TURNS. THE LOOSE SECUREMENT BOLTS ALLOWED PRODUCT TO ESCAPE FROM THE GAP BETWEEN THE FILL HOLE COVER AND THE FILL HOLE NOZZLE. THE PRODUCT OUTAGE WAS CHECKED AND DETERMINED TO BE ADEQUATE. ALL OTHER VALVES AND FITTINGS WERE FOUND TO BE SECURE. RESPONDERS PROPERLY TOOL TIGHTEN THE FILL HOLE COVER SECUREMENT BOLTS AND NEUTRALIZED ALL SPILLAGE ON THE SHELL OF PROX 15127. GROUND IMPACT AREAS THAT WERE FOUND WERE ALSO NEUTRALIZED.
column169: ENSURE SHIPPER’S PRE-TRIP INSPECTION PROCESS IS FULLY IMPLEMENTED AND VALIDATED AS IT RELATES TO THE TOTAL SECUREMENT AND MECHANICAL FITNESS OF ALL VALVES AND FITTINGS. IN THIS REGARD, THE BNSF ASSISTANT DIRECTOR OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MET WITH SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVES AT THE ORIGIN SHIPMENT LOCATION OF PROX 15127 ON 2/07/07 TO DISCUSS THE SECUREMENT DEFICIENCY OF PROX 15127 AND PROCESSES TO ELIMINATE ANY FUTURE SECUREMENT DEFICIENCIES OF THEIR SHIPMENTS.

column168: ON 01/28/07, CSXT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MANAGER RECEIVED A CALL FROM THE CUMBERLAND CAR SHOP REPORTING A SLOSH LEAK FROM THE TOP OF UTLX 208388.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND THE CUMBERLAND FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CONTACTED TO RESPOND TO THE RELEASE.  CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED (#01282007013) AND CONTRACTOR, SPECIALIZED PROFESSIONAL SERVICES, INC., WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE.  ALLEGANY COUTNY HAZ-MAT ARRIVED ON SITE AND FOUND THE LIQUID LINE VALVE IN THE OPEN POSITION AND THE LIQUID LINE PLUG LOOSE AND COMMENCED TO SECURE THE CAR.  SPSI ARRIVED AND RESEALED THE CAR AND VERIFIED ALL SERVICE EQUIPMENT WAS TOOL TIGHT.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR FINAL DESTINATION.    NARRI:  5(5+3+0)+(2+0)=80  cAUSE CODE+311

column168: ON 01/22/07 AT 1007, TRAIN MASTER REPORTED A STRONG ODOR LIKE SULFUR COMING FROM TANK CAR GATX 53497, AS WELL AS HAVING A RESIDUE ON THE SIDE OF CAR.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND A CSXT CONTRACTOR WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE.  UPON ARRIVAL, THEY DISCOVERED THE MANWAY BOLTS WERE LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT AND THE GASKET WAS MISSING.  ON 1/23/07, WEAVERTOWN ENVIRONMENTAL REPLACED THE GASKET AND BOLTS WERE SECURED WRENCH TIGHT.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO FINAL DESTINATION.    NARRI:  5(5+10)*(2+0)=60  CAUSE CODE=207

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: ON JANUARY 20, 2007, AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S TILFORD YARD FACILITY, FRA INSPECTORS REPORTED TANK CAR OLNX224014 (RESIDUE - LAST CONTAINED SODIUM HYDROXIDE SOLUTION) WITH LOOSE PLUGS AND FITTINGS.  CSX MANAGEMENT ISOLATED THE RAIL CAR AND INITIATED THEIR EMERGENCY RESPONSE PLAN.  CHEMTREC WAS CONTACTED (REPORT NUMBER 824223) AND THE SHIPPER, DSM CHEMICALS WAS NOTIFIED OF THE RELEASE.  CSX CONTRACTED SWS ENVIRONMENTAL TO RESPOND AND SECURE THE CONTAINER.  ONCE ON SITE, SWS REPRESENTATIVES FOUND THE FOLLOWING EXCEPTIONS:  LIQUID LINE CLOSURE PLUG LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT (3 TURNS) AND THE VAPOR LINE CLOSURE PLUG LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT (1-1/2 TURNS).  BOTH THE LIQUID AND VAPOR LINE VALVES WERE IN THE CLOSED POSITION.  THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP WAS CHECKED AND FOUND TO BE PROPERLY SECURED AS REQUIRED.  RESIDUAL PRODUCT WAS NOTED AROUND THE LIQUID AND VAPOR LINE VALVES ALONG WITH THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP AREA.  A SORBANT PAD WAS UTILIZED TO REMOVE THE RESIDUE SODIUM HYDROXIDE.  AFTER BEING PROPERLY SECURE, THE TANK CAR WAS RELEASED TO DESTINATION.    CAUSE CODE:  120  NARRI:  5(4-5-0)X(2+0)=90

column169: RETRAINING ON SAFE USE AND OPERATION OF THE FORKLIFT. WHEN ENTERING TRAILERS WITH PAILS, DRUMS OR TOTES LOADED AND HIDDEN BEHIND FREIGHT,WHEN USING BLADES, ENTER WITH CAUTION TO AVOID PUNCTURING PAILS. FREIGHT PLACED ON DOCK MUST BE SECURED AND PROPERLY BLOCKED AND SHROUDED TO AVOID EASY PUNCTURING FROM OTHER FREIGHT  OR FORKLIFT. DISCUSS DURING PRESHIFT ON THE SAFETY OF DOCKING, REMOVING AND TRANSFERRING CHEMICAL, LIQUID AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. BEING AWARE OF SURROUNDINGS WHEN WORKING. ON THE DOCK AND WHILE TRANSFERRING PACKAGES OF CHEMICALS, LIQUIDS OR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS! PAILS OF LIQUIDS, CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MUST BE  COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, MTY PALLETS AND PLYWOOD TO PREVENT EASY DAMAGED AND PUNCTURING. APPROPRIATE DISCIPLINE WAS ISSUED.

column168: On January 26, 2007 at 11:10 a.m., John Hutcherson, a contract crude oil transport driver working for Sunoco Logistics, notified the Sunoco Logistics area and district truck supervisors that a spill had occured at the Sunoco Logistics truck unloading station, located 2 miles north of the town of Barnsdall Oklahoma. The spill was a result of an unloading hose that became disconnected while the transport was pumping crude oil off into the unloading station tanks. Reportedly, the hose had been previously disconnected by another driver and then re-connected without properly securing the locking ears of the hose connection. The vibration of the pumping process caused the locking ears of the hose connection to vibrate open and the hose became disconnected from the header/piping. The pump of the transport unit continued to pump crude oil until approximately 109 barrels of crude oil had been released. Upon discovering the release, the driver shut down the pumping operation and contacted the Sunoco supervisors.     The Sunoco Logistics supervisors immediately began notifying Sunoco management and HES specialists. The HES specialists contacted the National Response Center at 12:34 p.m.,and called for a spill response team to respond to the area. The warm temperatures of the day had caused significant melting of ice and snow from a recent weather event. The run-off water from the melting ice and snow carried the crude oil across a neighboring field owned by another oil company, and on to a drainage ditch and ravine that acted as waterways during heavy rains. Sunoco employees began using shovels and a backhoe to construct flume dams to control the flow of the water and contain the crude oil. The transport unit loaded some of the spilled crude and several vacuum trucks were called in to begin skimming the oil from the run-off water. The spill response team arrived a short time later and several more flume dams were constructed to control the water and provide areas to skim the oil.      The skimming operations were successful, and only 4 barrels of crude were lost.The spill response company cleaned the affected areas by washing the area, deploying containment boom, removing affected grass, and using absorbents. Cleanup and soil remediation continues in the field area just south of the release, but wet conditons on the property have prohibited the use of equipment on the impacted area. The property is being monitored daily, and the cleanup operation will be completed as soon as the weather and drying conditions permit.
column169: Changes have been made to the unloading station hose connections, including using safety wire to secure the locking ears. All stations will be inspected to ensure locking ears are in use. Procedure changes have been made to eliminate the need to remove the unloading hoses, thereby reducing the likelyhood of the event recurring. All employees have been re-trained on the procedures of checking hose connections and continuosly monitoring pumping operations.

On January 26, 2007 ATL cargo accepted a shipment (AWB 006-0609-5670) for transport to SEA.  The shipment traveled on DL flight 1535/26JAN07 to SEA.  The shipment consisted of a "Lifting Jack Machine" and shipped/arrived as planned.  Post arrival, the shipper contacted ATL Cargo to advise that batteries may have been left on equipment.  ATL Cargo notified SEA and upon a closer inspection, 2 wet, non-spillable batteries were found installed in the equipment.  SEA cargo contacted Delta's Operation Control Center (OCC) for guidance.    SEA notified DL's Corporate DG group (DGMG) via our internal DG notification system. DGMG advised SEA to notify the local FAA Regional Office. FAA Special Agent David King reviewed the incident and photed the cargo in question.
column169: Shipper appeared to have knowledge of the hazardous materials prior to transport.  Unfortunately these batteries were invisible to Delta agent's accepting in ATL.  All Delta agents are currently trained to ask probing questions in an effort to determine whether hidden dangerous goods have been mistakenly included within a shipment.

column168: During the course of a roadside inspection conducted by the Louisiana State Police, a drip was noticed near the dust cap at the discharge piping. ON 01-16-07, 0840 HRS, CSX TRAIN Q50215 DERAILED 24 RAIL CARS (12 HAZMATS) ON THE MAIN LINE IN BROOKS, KY, CAUSING A FIRE AND THE RELEASE OF A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL THAT LEAD TO THE EVACUATION OF 40 HOMES IN THE IMMEDIATE AREA. CSX INITIATED THEIR EMERGENCY RESPONSE PLAN AND RESPONDED EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTORS TO THE SITE. THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE ON UTLX 667181 WAS RIPPED OFF THE RAIL CAR DURING THE DERAILMENT CAUSING PRODUCT TO LEAK OUT. DUE TO COLD AMBIENT TEMPERATURES THE PRODUCT SOLIDIFIED AT THE BOTTOM OUTLET, PREVENTING FURTHER SPILLAGE. PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED TO TRUCK FOR ALTERNATE DISPOSITION. REMEDIATION OF THE IMPACTED AREA CONTINUES.     ATARI : 2(5+3+O)*(3+4)=112   CAUSE CODE = E4BC

THIS CARGO SHIPMENT CAME APART ON THE LINE (RAMP BY GATE C-39) UPON INSPECTION THE DANGEROUS GOODS MENTIONED WERE DISCOVERED. THE RAMP AGENTS REPORTED TO CSM, WHO, GATHERED THE COMPLIANCE COORDINATOR TO INSPECT THE SHIPMENT. CARGO OPERATIONS CONTROL WAS CALLED TO VERIFY THAT THE CONTENTS WERE INDEED HAZARDOUS, WE REQUESTED MSDS FROM THE SHIPPER, AND VERIFIED THAT THE DYMEL 152 A WAS INDEED FOR CARGO AIRCRAFT ONLY. INFORMATION WAS GATHERED FROM OUR CARGO CONTRACTOR, AIR GENERAL., ON THE ACCEPTANCE AGENT WHO VERIFIED THAT THE SHIPMENT WAS EXEMPT AND THE DANGEROUS GOODS WERE UNDECLARED.     IT WAS THEN REPORTED TO THE FAA, AND A REPORT FILED WITH SOC.
column169: REPORTING THIS TO FAA, SHOULD ENSURE THAT EDUCATION FOR THE SHIPPER WILL PREVENT FUTURE OCCURANCE.

column168: AT 10:45 AM, THE CSXT MANAGER OF NETWORK OPERATIONS WAS NOTIFIED THAT PERSONNEL ON C70315 IN PATIO YARD, RAN FOUR CARS OUT THE SOUTH END OF THE YARD. THE CARS CONSISTED OF THREE LOADED HOPPER CARS OF PVC PLASTIC (UTCX 50878, UTCX 57559 & ROIX 57653) AND ONE LOADED TANK CAR OF BUTYL ACETATE (CELX 3329). THE CARS STRUCK THE UNMANNED LOCOMOTIVES FROM N25214 NEAR INDUSTRIAL ROAD IN IRVINE, KY AT 11:28 AM. THE TANK CAR FAILED AND RELEASED THE ENTIRE CONTENTS AND CAUGHT FIRE. LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT AND EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT PERSONNEL RESPONDED AND PUT OUT THE FIRE. A NEARBY CARHARTT TEXTILE FACILITY WAS EVACUATED AND AREA RESIDENTS WERE ADVISED TO “SHELTER-IN-PLACE”. FIRE DAMAGED THE TWO LOCOMOTIVES. AFTER THE FIRE WAS EXTINGUISHED, ENVIRONMENTAL REMEDIATION OF THE IMPACTED AREA BEGAN.     NARRI : 5(5+1+0)*(5+4) = 270   CAUSE CODE = 662

column168: COMPANY TRUCK WAS GOING NORTH ON TWO LANE COUNTY ROAD, CRESTED HILL AND SAW A SUB HAD CROSSED CENTER LINE AND WAS IN HIS LANE HEADED DIRECTLY AT OUR TRUCK.  VEHICLES HIT, IMPACT OCCURRED IN OUR LANE, HIT ON LEFT FRONT, BLOWING WHEEL COMPLETELY OFF OUR TRUCK.  OUR TRUCK WAS THEN STEERED ACROSS THE ROAD AND UP INTO AN EMBARKMENT WHICH FORCED OUR TRUCK TO OVERTRUN. OUR TRUCK WAS A BOBTAIL TRUCK, WITH TANK MOUNTED ON TRUCK FRAME.  A VENT LINE ON TOP OF THE TANK FAILED TO CLOSE OR OPENED AT IMPACT AND ABOUT 15 BARRELS LEAKED OUT OF TANK AND ONTO THE HILLSIDE AND DRAINAGE DITCH.  OUR CLEAN UP COMPANY USED A VACUUM TRUCK TO PICK UP ALL OIL SPILLED AND REMOVED ALL CONTAMINATED TOP SOIL.  REPLACEMENT SOD WAS BROUGHT IN AND AREA COMPLETELY CLEANED.  TOTAL VOLUME OF OIL LOST WAS LESS THAN TWO BBLS-WE RECOVERED ALL SPILLED OIL AND TOOK TO OUR RECLAIM YARD FOR TREATMENT AND EVENTUAL SALE.
column169: THE TANK VALVES AND FITTINGS ALL HELD EXCEPT FOR THE VENT LINE ON TOP WHICH LOOKS TO HAVE BEEN DAMAGED DURING THE ROLLOVER.  OVER INTERNAL ACCIDENT/RESPONSE PLAN WORKED WELL, CREWS WERE ONSITE WITHIN 15 MINUTES OF ACCIDENT AND THE CLEAN UP COMPANY DID AN OUTSTANDING JOB.  THE LOCAL LAND OWNER CALLED AND SAID HE WAS MOST IMPRESSED BY THE RAPIDITY AND THOROUGHNESS OF THE CLEAN UP.

column168: The sun momentarily blinded the driver's vision.  The propane truck's rear tire slipped off the edge of the road.  The driver continued to drive in the ditch to gain control of vehicle but struck a driveway and overturned.
column169: The company has a rollover prevention policy titled, "SLIP OFF STAY OFF" with cab posters and training reminders.  The idea is to bring the vehicle under control without attempting to radically change the path which can cause liquid load shifting and add to the potential for overturn.  After each such accident a committee reviews the investigative facts to determine whether the driver followed company safety practices and whether disciplinary actions are appropriate. Our employees receive recurrent training for defensive driving, proper backing techniques and how to prevent rollovers. Employees must pass a driver recertification test every three years.

column168: COURIER LOADED HIS VEHICLE AND PARKED IT IN THE SIGNATURE AIR PARKING LOT AT MITCHELL FIELD, MILWAUKEE, WI. BECAUSE OF AN ICE STORM HE REMAINED INSIDE SIGNATURE AIR AWAITING WEATHER IMPROVEMENT. HE DEPARTED SIGNATURE AIR AT APPROXIMATELY MIDNIGHT 13 JAN 2007 EN ROUTE TO MADISON, WI. HE STOPPED AT TWO REST AREAS EN ROUTE TO REMOVE ICE FROM WINDSHIELD, GET COFFEE AND GO TO REST ROOM. WHEN HE WENT TO THE REAR OF HIS VEHICLE TO REMOVE A PACKAGE FOR DELIVERY IN MADISON HE NOTED DAMAGE TO THE VEHICLE CANOPY AND LIFT GATE BEZEL. HE DISCOVERED THAT THE SUBJECT PACKAGE WAS MISSING, AND PRESUMABLY STOLEN. HE CALLED THE MILWAUKEE COUNTY SHERIFF, RETURNED TO MILWAUKEE, AND MET WITH DEPUTY J. DUNCAN, BADGE 167.     ACCORDING TO NEWS MEDIA REPORTS ON FRIDAY, JANUARY 19, 2007 A MAN CLAIMS THAT HE SAW THE SUBJECT PACKAGE FALL FROM A VEHICLE IN MILWAUKEE BUT WAS UNABLE TO FLAG THE DRIVER DOWN. HE FURTHER STATED THAT HE CALLED THE 800 NUMBER ON THE PACKAGE, WHICH IS THE CHEMTREC 24 EMERGENCY RESPONSE TELEPHONE NUMBER, GOT A RECORDING AND LEFT A MESSAGE. CHEMTREC HAS NO RECORD OF SUCH CALL. HE TURNED THE PACKAGE INTO THE WAUWATOSA, WI SHERIFF’S SUBSTATION THURSDAY EVENING, JANUARY 13, 2007. THE PACKAGE WAS TURNED OVER TO THE CONSIGNEE WHO STATED THAT IT WAS IN "PRISTINE" CONDITION.   THE CONTENTS OF THE PACKAGE WERE RETURNED BY THE CONSIGNEE TO BRISTOL MYERS SQUIBB, AND THE PACKAGING IS CURRENTLY IN POSSESSION OF THE FBI IN MILWAUKEE. PICTURES OF THE PACKAGING WERE TAKEN WHICH SHOW THAT THE PACKAGING WAS IN EXCELLENT CONDITION AND DID NOT EXHIBIT DAMAGE COMMENSURABLE WITH FALLING OFF A VEHICLE ONTO A HIGHWAY. THE PICTURES WERE SUBMITTED TO EMPLOYEE, SENIOR TRANSPORTATION ENFORCEMENT SPECIALIST, OFFICE OF HAZARDOUS MATERILALS ENFORCEMENT, PHMSA, US DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION, WASHINGTON, DC.

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS AT THE B/P AMOCO LOADING RACK IN OREGON, OH. OUR DRIVER, OVERLOADED, WENT ACROSS THE INNER PLANT SCALES, NOTICED THAT HE WAS ABOUT 800 LBS. OVERWEIGHT. HE WAS NOTIFIED BY THE LADY AT THE SCALE THAT HE NEEDED TO GO BACK TO OFFLOAD THE OVERWEIGHT AMOUNT. WHEN HE DID, HE WAITED FOR A WHILE AND NO ONE SHOWED. THE DRIVER DECIDED TO GO AHEAD AND HOOK UP TO GET READY TO UNLOAD AND AFTER HE HOOKED UP HIS HOSE AND OPENED THE VALVE, HE DIDN'T FEEL ANY PRODUCT COMING OUT, SO HE DECIDED TO CRACK OPEN THE HOSE A LITTLE BIT TO SEE AND WHEN HE DID THE PRODUCT STARTED TO FLOW, PUSHING THE HOSE OUT OF EMPLOYEE'S HANDS AND APPROXIMATELY 100 GALLONS WENT ON THE GROUND. AT THE TERMINAL BEFORE HE WAS ABLE TO GET IT SHUT OFF. B/P AMOCO PERSONNEL CLEANED THE MESS WITH INNER PLANT PERSONNEL. NO COST HAVE BEEN SUBMITTED YET FOR THE CLEAN-UP OF PRODUCT.
column169: THE DRIVER HAS BEEN BARRED FROM THE TERMINAL, ALL OTHER DRIVERS HAVE BEEN WARNED THAT THEY ARE NOT TO START ANY PART OF UNLOADING, UNLESS THERE IS PERSONNEL FROM THE PLANT THERE AT THE TIME THE PROCEDURE IS NEEDED. ALSO NO DRIVER IS SUPPOSE TO CRACK THE HOSE AWAY FROM THE TANK WHEN THE VALVES ARE OPEN.

column168: ON 1/24/07 DURING SWITCHING OPERATIONS, THE CREW NOTICED TANK CAR SCMX 4311, LOAD PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, N.O.S., LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF CAR. THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR, GARNER ENVIRONMENTAL, WAS DISPATCHED TO SCENE. UPON ARRIVAL, GARNER ENVIRONMENTAL INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND THE MANWAY GASKET WAS AN IMPROPER SIZE. THE GASKET WAS REPLACED AND THE MANWAY COVER WAS SECURED WRENCH TIGHT. CAR WAS RELEASED FOR FINAL DESTINATION. ALTHOUGH SHELL OIL OFFERED THIS RAIL CAR, IT WAS LOADED BY INTERCONTINENTAL TERMINAL CORPORATION (ITC), DEER PARK, TX. ITC WAS RESPONSIBLE TO ENSURE PACKAGE INTEGRITY.     NARRI : 5(2+1+0)*(2+0)=30   CAUSE CODE = 211

ON 01/19/2007 AT 2100, THE PSCC WAS CONTACTED BY CSXT TRAIN MASTER, THAT TANK CAR GATX 37321, LOAD ETHYLENE GLYCOL, WAS REPORTED LEAKING FROM THE UNDERSIDE OF THE RAILCAR. NOTIFICATION WAS MADE TO THE STATE OF TN., AND SHIPPER, EQUISTAR CHEMICAL. A CSXT CONTRACTOR, HEPACO ENVIROMENTAL, WAS CALLED TO INSPECT THE RAIL CAR. THE CONTRACTOR REPORTED THAT THE LEAK WAS COMING FROM THE AUXILARY VALVE STEM PACKING GLAND. BOTH NUTS WERE LOOSE THAT HELD THE PACKING IN PLACE ALLOWING PRODUCT TO SLOWLY LEAK. THE NUTS WERE TIGHTENED, STOPPING THE LEAK. THE RAIL CAR WAS FORWARDED FOR DELIVERY TO ITS FINAL DESTINATION.     NARRI: 5(5+1+5)*(2+0)=110   CAUSE CODE = 296

A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING A 55-GALLON DRUM OF HAZARDOUS WASTE LIQUID WAS EN ROUTE BACK TO THE ORIGINAL SHIPPER OF THE CONTAINER. THE MATERIAL IN QUESTION WAS BEING RETURNED TO THE ORIGINAL SHIPPER AS IT WAS OFFERED IN ERROR. DURING THE COURSE OF TRANSPORTATION, THE DRIVER WAS MAKING A ROUTINE STOP AT A TRUCK WASH FACILITY WHEN HE NOTICED A SMALL AMOUNT OF MATERIAL LEAKING FROM THE BACK DOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATLEY STOPPED HIS VEHICLE, DONNED THE APPROPRIATE PPE AND PROCEEDED TO PLACE THE LEAKING CONTAINER INTO A SUITABLE OVERPACK. ONCE SECURED, THE DRIVER CONTACTED HIS HOME DISPATCHER WHO, IN TURN NOTIFIED THE LOUISIANNA STATE POLICE. THE DRIVER ALSO NOTIFIED THE MANAGEMENT OF THE TRUCK STOP FACILITY. AN IN-HOUSE RESPONSE CREW WAS IMMEDIATELY DISPATCHED AND IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY 15 GALLONS OF MATERIAL WAS RELEASED TO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER, THE DRIVEWAY LEADING INTO THE TRUCK WASH BAY AND A SECTION OF CONCRETE FLOOR IN THE BAY. UPON ARRIVAL, THE RESPONSE CREW PROCEEDED TO ABSORB ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH A SUITABLE ABSORBENT MATERIAL, CLEANED ALL CONTAMINATED AREAS AND CONTAINERIZED ALL CLEAN-UP DEBRIS FOR DISPOSAL AT A FULLY LICENSED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY. UPON COMPLETION OF CLEAN-UP ACTIVITIES, A COMPANY REPRESENTATVE MET WITH A MEMBER OF THE LOUISIANNA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY AND THE PROPERTY OWNER AND IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE SITE WAS PROPERLY CLEANED.
column169: IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE OF THIS SITUATION, BETTER PRE-TRANSPORT INSPECTIONS WILL NEED TO BE CONDUCTED TO IDENTIFY CONTAINERS THAT HAVE SUSPECT INTEGRITY CONDITIONS. THIS INSPECTION NEEDS TO BE CONDUCTED BOT BY THE SHIPPER/OFFEROR AND THE TRANSPORTER ACCEPTING A CONTAINER FOR TRANSPORT. CONTAINERS THAT SHOW EVIDENCE OF DAMAGE OR STRUCTURAL INTEGRITY DEFECTS MUST EITHER BE RECONTAINERIZED OR PLACED IN A SUITABLE OVERPACK PRIOR TO BEING ACCEPTED FOR TRANSPORTATION.

The Manager of Environmental Field Operations, was notified and responded. All required notifications were made. At 05:16 PM, He advised he was on scene and failed to secure the release by wrench tightening the flange. He further stated the release was a few drops continuing to be collected in a bucket and the Consignee would transload the tankcar to a truck on 1/31/07. UPDATE: At 630 PM, he advised he was departing the scene after remediating a minute amount of frozen soil contamination.

column168: At 2238hrs on 1-27-07, The Manager of Terminal Operations advised conductor reported a release of product from the top of tank car GATX 64585, which was located on track 308 of the Englewood train yard, Houston, TX. He stated the release occurred while the car was moved. He also indicated that someone had inhaled vapors from the product, was coughing and complaining of tightness in his chest. Upon being advised, Mgr. responded, and requested the RMCC make shipper notification via Chem-Trec, and that CTEH be contacted regarding the employee exposure. On arrival, the mgr met someone who was being examined by company nurs. He appeared to be normal, he indicated that he came in contacted with the vapors, and had some product spill onto his shirt and boots while the car was being moved. At 2301 hrs,Albemarle Corporation, was conferenced with Mgr.  and requested MSDS information is provided.   Inspection of the   car by Mgr.  revealed the composition rupture disk housing to he attached with 3 studs on top of the manway cover. The disk retainer, inspection cap, and disk were laying on the side of the manway cover not secured within the safety vent assembly. The threads of the disk retainer were intact, not stripped. The rupture disk was compromised from the bottom side of the disk, however the top side was intact.   Upon replacement of the frangible disk housing and frangable disk, the car was secure from further release.   Arrangements were made by the Manager of Logistics of Tessenderlo Davison Companies, LLC, the actual owner of the product, to have the car cleaned & deodorized by Garner Environmental. The car and immediate area around the car were neutralized on site and did not require any additional remediation. At 043Ohrs on 1-28-07, normal operations resumed. Car GATX 64585 was released for transportation and allowed to continue onto destination without further incident.   At 0l00hrs on 1-28-07, after continued   monitoring by a Nurse and under the advisement of CTEH, Conductor was cleared to resume normal work duties, and returned to work.

column168: North Platte Corridor Manager, reported Tankcar GATX 57610 was observed with possible residue on its side and a possible loose manway cover at the West Bowl, Yard 1, Track 54 in the Bailey Yard, in North Platte, NE.  Manager of Chemical Transportation Safety, was notified and responded. At 06:46 AM, Keeling advised that the tankcar had a blown rupture disk. The rupture disk in the tankcar was a Zook RC165 and was replaced with an Oseco HPRC1 65 per the shipper contact, Basic Chemicals company. Manager of Chemical Transportation Safety, further advised the tankcar would be decontaminated by Hazmat Response Incorporated, Environmental Contractor, using sodium bicarbonate and water. At 9:39 AM, Manager of Chemical Transportation Safety, advised all residue was neutralized, the remediation completed, and the tankcar released to normal operations..

column168: Car Department Director, reported a vapor release above Tankcar UTLX 13002 as it entered the north yard on Train MPVSC 02,in Salt Lake City, Utah. Manager of Chemical Transportation Safety, was notified and responded. Appropriate notifications were made. The train was isolated to track number five. At 09:40 AM, Manager of Chemical Transportation Safety advised he inspected the tankcar and found a broken rupture disk which caused the release. The material was contained to the top of the tankcar.  Advised that the released product and been neutralized, the rupture disk replaced, and tankcar released to transportation.

The UPRR Manager of Yard Operation, Alfalfa Yard El Paso, TX reported tankcar UTLX 201600 released product from the top of the car. Manager of Chemical Transportation Safety, was notified and responded. Manager of Chemical Transportation Safety, discovered the car had released product due to a loose liquid line valve. Manager of Chemical Transportation Safety, tightened the liquid line valve, stopping the release. Manager of Chemical Transportation Safety, inspected the car and discovered the liquid line valve closure plug loose, not leaking and the vapor valve closure plug loose, not leaking. Manager of Chemical Transportation Safety, tightened all the loose plugs and notified Viva Environmental to respond to clean the product from the top of the car. The car was reinspected and released to destination with no other exceptions. Shipper was notified via Chemtrec.

column168: Yardmaster, reported tank car UTLX 205957, had derailed and an unknown amount of product had been released onto the ground at the Fourth Street Yard, Los Angeles, CA. Yardmaster stated no waterways were affected and requested the fire department respond for assistance. Manager, Chemical Transportation Safety, was notified and responded. RMCC established a conference call with Manager, City of Los Angeles Fire Department, Haz Mat, who stated he was on scene and advised the release rate was approximately one half gallon per minute from the tank car that was derailed onto its side. City of Los Angeles Fire Department advised the product appeared to be leaking from the six bolt manway cover plate. Manager advised the manway bolts could be loose and requested the Haz Mat Team attempt to tighten all 6 manway bolts. The release was stopped after all of the manway bolts had been tightened. Inspection of the site developed tank car UTLX 205957 was on track #703, however, was not clear of the switch to adjacent track #704. Several tank cars rolled out of track #704, and side swiped the tank car, causing it to roll onto it’s side. The car was re-railed without incident. Once the safety appliances are repaired, the car will be delivered to the consignee.

column168: 30 PAILS WERE STACKED 3 HIGH ON A USED PALLET WITH ONE MISSING SLAT. WHEN THE TRAILER BACKED TO THE DOCK, THE PAILS SHIFTED AND ONE ROW FELL INTO THE SPACE LEFT BY THE MISSING SLAT. THE PAILS OVERTURNED, THE LID CAME LOOSE ON ONE PAIL AND APPROX 2 GAL. OF PAINT SPILLED ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR. CARDBOARD WAS PLACED UNDER TRAILER AND OIL DRY WAS PLACED ON THE SPILLED PAINT. THE LEAKING PAILS WAS FOUND AND TURNED UPRIGHT, AND PLACED IN A 30 GAL RECOVERY DRUM. THE CLEANUP WASTE WAS PLACED IN A 6 GALL RECOVERY PAIL. THE PAINT ON THE TRAILER FLOOR THAT WAS NOT ABSORBED, DRIED ON THE FLOOR. THE SPILL LASTED APPROX 5 MINUTES AND THE CLEANUP APPROX 1 HOUR.
column169: THE SHIPPER SHOULD HAVE USED A BETTER QUALITY SKID WITH ALL SLATS IN PLACE. THE PAILS SHOULD HAVE BEEN STACKED 2 HIGH INSTEAD OF 3 HIGH AND THERE SHOULD HAVE BEEN ENOUGH SHRINK WRAP AROUND THE PAILS TO PREVENT THEM FROM SHIFTING OR FALLING OVER. THE EMPLOYEE WILL BE RETRAINED TO BE ABLE TO BETTER INDENTIFY FAULTY PALLETS AND OTHER PROBLEMS IN ORDER TO HELP THE SHIPPER PREPARE THE SHIPMENT PROPERLY FOR TRANSPORTATION.

column42: RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL, EXCEPTED PACKAGE-ARTICLES MANUFACTURED FROM NATURAL URANIUM OR DEPLETED URANIUM OR NATURAL THORIUM
column168: At approximately 3:15pm on January 9, 2007 a Miller Compressing truck picked up a 12 yard luggar box from the GE Healthcare facility at 7624 S. 10th Street in Oak Creek. This facility is staffed with employees from ACE World Wide in a co- employment agreement and ACE is not licensed to receive, handle, use or store radioactive materials. This aluminum breakage box was packed by employees of ACE. This luggar box was then transported to the Miller Compressing yard at 1640 West Bruce Street in Milwaukee. Upon arrival, the incoming material set off a radiation detector, it was sent through again to verify the results and set it off again. At this point a Miller Project Engineer attempted to reach the contact person at the GE facility; he was successful in leaving a voicemail requesting a call back. He then quarantined the luggar box and area surrounding it until it could be investigated further.    The next morning the contents of the box were dumped on a hard surface and four pieces, scattered in the load, were discovered to be the source of the radiation. Shortly thereafter, employees from ACE World Wide and GE Healthcare were on site to investigate. The results were as follows:    •These articles were identical in appearance as black painted bars, approximately 8    inches in length and approximately 1 inch (maximum) in section.  •Halfway along the length of the bar a hollow tube (approx 6-7” in length) was    fastened that projected out at a right angle to the bar, thus making a “T” shape.  •A movable rod was positioned inside the hollow tube with a threaded end at one end    and a knurled knob at the other so as to be able to fasten the bar to some other     equipment or fixture.  •There were no labels that indicated the radionuclide or quantity of radioactive    material.     1.The only obvious markings were a white painted trefoil and the number 2040        followed by a roman numeral with each bar having the numeral I though IV.     2.The word “Radioactive” was stamped on one end of the black bar, partially        obscured by paint.     3.The word “Uranium” as stamped on the other end of the bar, with “8/95” stamped        on one of the edges.  •Radiation levels of each bar were consistently 1.5 mR/hr at the surface and 0.16    mR/hr at 1 ft with the beta shield closed on the ion chamber.  •With the shield open, the measurements were I 7.7-mR/hr surface and 1.6 mR/hr at 1    ft.  •Wipe samples taken from all four articles indicated that there was no removable    contamination.    After checking all the radiation levels and the fact that there is no removable contamination, it has been decided, that there was no danger to the ACE personnel that handled the pieces or the Miller personnel that transported the shipment.
column169: GE Healthcare conducted an internal investigation to determine the origin of these pieces and concluded that they were not from any GE equipment. GE Healthcare is wrrking with Miller Compressing to ensure proper disposal of the items. All ACE World Wide employees were retrained on hazardous communications and procedures to folllow in the event of a repeat situation to ensure their safety. GE Healthcare and ACE World Wide are conducting ongoing meetings to make sure that a situation like this never occurs again.

column168: A BNSF road switcher shoving railcars into an industrial lead off of the main track derailed four railcars including covered hopper INTX 5026. The cause of this derailment was attributed to defective or missing rail fasteners which allowed the rail to roll. INTX 5026 was leaning and leaking product granules from the two end hopper outlets. The middle outlet of this three hopper configuration covered hopper railcar remained intact and closed. BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders reported that the outlet gates appeared to be in the locked position with no seals applied. The A & B-end outlets twisted open a couple of inches possibly from either faulty or damaged operating mechanisms. Opening of the outlets allowed product granules to escape between the rails for several car lengths. It appeared that most of the product granules in the A & B-end hoppers escaped. A BNSF environmental contractor vacuumed the spillage and it was scheduled for approved landfill disposal as a special waste.

column168: A BNSF westbound intermodal stack train derailed five articulated flatcars on the main track. The cause of the derailment was attributed to a catastrophic container floor failure of an intermodal container overloaded with corn. Intermodal container GESU 461255 was riding atop one of the intermodal flatcars that derailed. GESU 461255 sustained exterior damage but remained upright. During the process of clearing derailed rail equipment, GESU 461255 was placed on its side and removed from the main track area. GESU 461255 was later up-righted. When the lading inside GESU 461255 was checked, one damaged 250 gallon IBC was noted dripping product from the pressure relief type closure cap. The dripping ebbed as the ambient temperatures lowered and partially solidified the product within. Three other identical IBC’s (plastic IBC with aluminum wrapped insulation surrounded by a aluminum cage) had some structural damage but were not leaking. The contents of the four damaged IBC’s were transferred into a tanker truck. The remaining 12 IBC’s had repairs made to their outside cages and stored in a dry van for further disposition instructions. The entire shipment destined for export in the 16 IBC’s was later rejected for further transport. The product was degraded by the freeze/thaw cycles from ambient outside temperature fluctuations. All of the product from the 16 BC’s was waste profiled for incineration.

column169: On The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR), shippers are immediately notified of all HAZMAT releases.  For non-accident releases (a.k.a. package or closure defects), where possible, shippers (responsible party) are requested to respond, repair and remediate.  By immediately involving the shipper, in-depth knowledge of the release cause is gained by the same organization that can implement process changes to prevent recurrence. For non-accident related releases, the shipper should be contacted directly for details associated with actions taken to prevent recurrence.

column168: The driver was unloading fuel oil at this bulk plant and was attempting to fill 4 different tanks at the same time.  These tanks are all hooked to one common manifold.  As each individual tank became full, the driver would shut off the valve on the manifold that lead to that tank.  The driver inadvertently shut the valve to a tank that was not full and left a tank that was full open.  This resulted in a spill.     The driver contacted the owner of the bulk plant immediately following the incident and notified his company manager of the release the following morning. Then the MPCA and MN Duty Officer were notified.  The company manager contacted Bay West, an enviromental emergency response company, to clean the affected area.  This matter was cleaned up in approximately 36 hours.
column169: All drivers of this company were reminded of the correct procedures to be followed when unloading at any bulk facility.  The driver, who caused this incident, was terminated from employment with this company.

column168: Driver stated he was traveling on the SW Energy mine access road at roughly 20-25 mph. Road was on a slight upgrade and pitched on both sides. Road is gravel, packed, but muddy with some rutting. Driver advised as he was cresting a small hill as another truck approached him, so he moved over to shoulder to make room. Driver indicated as the gear grabbed the “pup” (trailer #2) began to slide on mud over the right edge. Driver tried to man uver vehicle back onto road but the pindle hook broke causing pup to to detatch and roll over shoulder to right side. Driver stopped immediately and checked for loss of product. At time of roll over no product was lost. He immediately called 911, company dispatch, as well as mine Safety. Nevada Highway patrol responded and left making no report due to private property. Atlas towing was called for cleanup and towing. Mine personnel came on scene to assist in pumping off product. At this time is when there was product lost, roughly 200 gallons. The mine personnel and Atlas had to hook up multiple compressors to pressurize the tank to pump off the product. Product tempurature in trailer was roughly 190 degrees so when the lost liquid hit the below 30 degree tempuratures the fertilizer began to set up before it could absorb into soil. Atlas and Newmont Mine Safety pumped off trailer, scraped soil, disposed of set up material in their holding pond, and deemed location clean. LW Miller Safety made a report to the EPA, report # 823120. At that time I soke to a “Nicole” 800-300-2193 x3 that advised that due to the amount lost, circumstances of set up product, and it having been private property that no additional reporting was neccessary. We apologize for our failure to complete this form as needed assure you that we will not fail again.
column169: Driver was suspended at time of incident and brought to our facility for training and discussion. We feel our driver is a capable individual who had made and misjudged his position on the road and under estimated the slickness of the soil.  Driver acknowledged that he could and should have stopped to allow other to pass and that chains may have been a good choice as well.

column168: Handling company, MENZIES, damagaed a HAZMAT drum when staging ULD for Export flight. They used a forklift to push the ULD back onto a transport vehicle. The forklift blade punchured the 220 L ( 55 gal) drum near the bottom. The contents then leaked out. The fire department was called and was supervising the area. A HAZMAT company was called and they performed the actual clean up with absorbant material. The waste material was collected and marked and will be disposed of in accordance with disposal laws.   The handling company , MENZIES, was mandated to do the following corrective action:   1. Consult with the Lufthansa staff in such a situation ( ramp agent, loadmaster or supervisor).   2. Be aware of the HAZMAT/DGR tag and DGR hazard labels on the packages and handle all DGR ULD's with extreme care.   3. Never move or handle a HAZMAT/DGR ULD with a forklift.Import as well as Export ULDs.

column42: RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL, EXCEPTED PACKAGE-LIMITED QUANTITY OF MATERIAL
column168: On October 4, 2007, Energy Northwest discovered that an undeclared shipment of hazardous material had occurred. Communications between Energy Northwest personnel revealed that on January 23, 2007 an NCS Model LMP-10 Freon monitor, containing a 300 mCi Tritium source, was transferred to NCS Corporation for calibration without marking the shipment as UN2910 as required by 49 CFR 173.421(a). The monitor was shipped from Richland, WA on January 23, 2007 via UPS and received in Columbus, OH on January 24, 2007. The return shipment of the instrument to Energy Northwest was received on February 12, 2007 and was designated as containing radioactive material.  This LMP-10 Freon monitor is maintained under a general license subject to the requirements of 10 CFR 31 and Department of Transportation regulations in 49 CFR. Following identification of this incident, Energy Northwest initiated immediate corrective action to minimize the potential for future undeclared shipments of radioactive material. Specifically, Energy Northwest conducted a site wide search of Columbia Generating Station and surrounding areas to identify and control generally licensed devices. Furthermore, Energy Northwest personnel in a position to process the shipment of generally licensed devices were briefed to ensure heightened awareness.  Energy Northwest initiated an apparent cause evaluation of the circumstances surrounding the January 23, 2007 shipment. This incident is similar to an event that Energy Northwest reported to the Department of Transportation in a letter dated August 17, 2007 (Reference). The cause of both of these incidents can be directly attributed to a lack of clear identification alerting warehouse personnel that the article presented for shipment contained hazardous material. This condition is attributed to a less-than- adequate understanding of the regulations governing generally licensed devices by all responsible stewards. Had more robust corporate processes governing the control of generally licensed devices been implemented at the time of the January 23, 2007 shipment, this incident would likely not have occurred.  There were no consequences associated with this event. There is no evidence that the sources leaked during shipment. Furthermore, Tritium is a low activity isotope and during radioactive decay emits a beta-particle that is easily shielded. With these sources contained within the confines of the instrument housing as well as the associated shipping container, the potential for radioactive exposure of any individual as a result of this shipment was negligible.
column169: Similar to the incident reported in a lefter dated August 17, 2007 (Reference), the cause of the January 23, 2007 undeclared shipment was the result of less-than-adequate processes governing the control of generally licensed devices. At the time this shipment was discovered (October 4, 2007), Energy Northwest was in the process of implementing corrective actions to preclude this type of event. Specific actions Energy Northwest is pursuing focus on enhancing formal processes governing generally licensed devices. These processes are to be implemented through enhanced training, procedures, and oversight to ensure consistent compliance with applicable regulations. Furthermore, Energy Northwest will appoint an individual for each licensed device to ensure day-to-day compliance with appropriate regulations and requirements as stipulated in 10 CFR 31.5(c)(12). Each generally licensed device associated with Columbia Generating Station will be clearly identified to inform station personnel of the device’s controlled status and appointed custodian. The shipment of the LMP-1 0 is a legacy issue that occurred well before the identification and implementation of these corrective actions. Following complete implementation of these corrective actions, the occurrence of undeclared shipments of this nature is expected to be precluded.

column168: Our driver James Crumbach arrived at Red Land High School at 5:15 am. He found tank #2 and stuck the tank, which had a reading of 74". He then found tank #1 and stuck the tank, which had a reading of 23 1/2". James did not know if tank #1 was a 96" or a 120" tank. He used a drop tube to deliver to tank #1. James went to the cab of his truck to get his tank chart book so when he took a reading after the delivery, he would know the size of the tank.    James heard the sound of the drop tube change. He looked back and oil was running out the top of the fill. He ran back to shut off the trailer. When he shut off the trailer, oil shot out of the tank 4 1/2 to 5 feet high until all of the air was out of the tank.    James went to the boiler room and got the man on duty. Both men got oil dry and spill pads and blocked the storm drain off. The man on duty then called for more help and oil dry. After the oil dry was down, James took the 2" cap off (he was told you need to have that open to unload). James then unloaded the rest of the load. He stuck the tank and got a reading of 97". Approximately 200 gallons were spilled.
column169: The tank that was being delivered into was equipped with a remote fill that has thread fittings instead of the standard 4" adapter fitting. The driver used a drop tube to make the delivery. The vent on the tank was not venting properly and as a result the tank built up back pressure and pushed product out of the fill pipe.    Farm & Home has sent a letter to the School District encouraging them to correct the venting situation and to replace the fill pipe with an adapter so that a current-day 4" conventional fitting can be used.    We have reviewed all unloading procedures with our drivers as well as the communication with school district personnel to avoid a similar situation in the future.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH NOT MORE THAN 51% ACID
column168: American Airlines, flight 60, aicraft 7BT, arrived from NRT on DFW gate D33 at 1514 hours. The ramp crew attempted to offload the bulk cargo as normal. There was international mail listed in the aft bulk cargo compartment. When one of the ramp clerks entered the bulk compartment, he noticed some of the mail bags had what appeared to be chemical burns on them. A box labeled, "plate chemicals", was with the mail bags. It was wet and when moved smoke was observed coming from the box and mail bags. Ramp crew evacuated and contacted management.    American Airlines contacted contract spill responder, Eagle Construction, and they arrived the same time as the USPS Inspector. The USPS Inspector cleared Eagle to test the spilled material and it was determined to be sulfuric acid. Eagle was then cleared to clean up the acid and they bagged up the material. The USPS Inspector then took everything with him.

Shipment fell over inside of delivery truck, refused by consignee and returned to BQN facility. While personnel were working to straighten shipment a cover came off and batteries were discovered. After inspecting the shipment and documents, not special provisions were entered on the shipping document and batteries were found to be non compliant to 49 CFR 173.159 (d) (1). John Connelly of the FAA Puerto Rico office was immediately notified for inspection and shipment was held at BQN

column62: Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage; Human Error
column168: AT 2019 HOURS AT SELKIRK YARD, NATX 29073, A LOADED METHANOL TANK CAR WAS CUT OFF FROM THE CREST OF THE HUMP. NATX 29073 (93RD CAR) STALLED ON THE C-21/22 SWITCH IN THE CLASSIFICATION, YARD MLMX 270 (104TH CAR), AN EMPTY HIGH SIDE GONDOLA, WAS DESTINED FOR TRACK C-23. THE AUTO PROTECTION SYSTEM WAS OVERRIDDEN TO TRIM THE CLASSIFICATION TRACKS. MLMX 270 STRUCK NATX 29073 IN THE A-END OF THE TANK CAR. THE STRUCTURAL RIB OF MLMX 270 PUNCTURED THE HEAD OF TANK CAR NATX 29073 AT THE FOUR O’CLOCK POSITION. THE IMPACT CREATED A 6”X 8” HOLE, RELEASING METHANOL AND RESULTING IN A FIRE. CSXT INITIATED THE TERP — TRANSPORTATION EMERGENCY RESPONSE PLAN, CALLED 911, THE CSXT PSCC AND HAZMAT MGR. EAST END EMPLOYEES OF THE CLASS YARD WERE MOVED TO THE TOP END BUILDING AND THE LOCOMOTIVE SHOP. THE INCIDENT AREA WAS ISOLATED. THE PSCC HAZMAT CALL DUTY OFFICER CONTACTED MILLER ENVIRONMENTAL, AMEC, CTEH FOR TESTNET RESPONSE AND REACT ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES TO RESPOND AND WORK WITH LOCAL EMERGENCY RESPONDERS AND OFFICIALS. THE SELKIRK, ELSMERE AND BETHLEHEM FIRE DEPARTMENTS STAGED AND SETUP TO EXTINGUISH THE FIRE. THE FIRE CHIEF USING EMERGENCY RESPONSE INFORMATION MADE AN EVACUATION AREA OF 0.5 MILES FROM THE SITE. THIRTY-SEVEN HOMES WERE ASKED TO EVACUATE OR SHELTER IN PLACE, TOTALING SIXTY AREA RESIDENTS. THE FIRE DEPARTMENTS USING ATC FOAM AGENT WERE ABLE TO EXTINGUISH THE FIRE AT 2121 HOURS. MILLER ENVIRONMENTAL WITH ASSISTANCE FROM THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND PAUL WATSON JR. (CSXT SENTINEL) PLACED A MAGNETIC PLATE PATCH OVER THE HOLE AND SEALED THE REMAINING AREA WITH PLUG & DIKE TO STOP THE LEAK AT 2210 HOURS. MILLER ENVIRONMENTAL USING A VAC TRUCK TRANSFERRED THE REMAINING PRODUCT FROM THE TANK CAR INTO A FRAC TANK STAGED ON SITE. APPROXIMATELY 18,871 GALLONS OF METHANOL WAS RELEASED FROM THE TANK CAR. THE METHANOL THAT DID NOT BURN MIXED WITH THE ATC FOAM AND WATER, POOLED AND RAN INTO A NEARBY DRAIN CULVERT THAT WENT TO CSXT RETENTION POND. NO PRODUCT LEFT CSXT PROPERTY. AREA RESIDENTS WERE RELEASED FROM THE EVACUATION, SHELTAR IN PLACE AT 2230 HOURS. CHEMTREC REPORT 01042007-054.

column168: FRA Inspector Matsinger notified CSXT Hazardous Materials, Manager Austin that she was inspecting tank cars and took exception to GATX 59313. This car was located at CSXT Bayview yard. Inspector Matsinger provided an inspection report that stated "audible vapor was noted around safety vent assembly". Inspector Matsinger requested CSX arrange for car to be examined further. REACT Environmental was dispatched by CSXT Hazardous Materials. REACT determined that the rupture disk was intact, flange bolts on the liquid line were not tool tight and bolts on the fill hole cover were also loose. REACT properly secured the tank car before releasing to transportation.    Chemtrec Report# 01192007063    Cause code=:224 & 242    NARRI: 5(4+5+0)(2+0)=90

column168: CSXT Hazardous Materials was notified that ACFX 78315, Residue last contained Flammable liquid, was dripping from the bottom outlet valve area. Arizona Chemical was contacted and contracted Rescar to respond to secure the tank car. Rescar determined that the top operated bottom outlet valve was in the open position and the bottom cutlet gasket was deteriorated. Rescar closed the valve and replaced the gasket to properly secure the car. No further exceptions noted and tank car was released. JANUARY 14, 2007, A PASSENGER TRAVELING FROM HILO, HAWAII TO KAHULUI MAUI RESULTED IN AN INCIDENT OCCURRING AT ITS FINAL DESTINATION. THE PASSENGER CHECKED IN HIS BACKPACK AS BAGGAGE IN HILO. THE PASSENGER AND BAGGAGE BOTH DEPARTED HILO AND WAS OFFLOADED IN HONOLULU TO CHANGE AIRCRAFTS. WHILE OFFLOADING THE BAGS AT ITS FINAL DESTINATION, KAHULUI, MAUI, AN ALOHA AIRLINES RAMP SERVICE AGENT NOTICED A PUFF COMING FROM THE DETACHABLE SIDE POCKET OF THE BACKPACK IN QUESTION. HE INITIALLY THOUGHT IT WAS POWDER AND REALIZED HE SMELT SMOKE. HE THEN REMOVED THE BACKPACK FROM THE AIRCRAFT AND FULLY DOUSED THE POCKET WITH WATER, PUTTING OUT WHATEVER WAS BURNING. THE RAMP AGENT THEN DELIVERED THE BACKPACK TO THE BAGGAGE CLAIMS OFFICE WHERE NOTIFICATION TO THE TSA AND PASSENGER WAS MADE.     THE TSA OPENED THE BACKPACK AND FOUND STRIKE ANYWHERE MATCHES, STORM PROOF MATCHES, SCISSORS, ITEMS THOUGHT TO HAVE BEER A SURVIVAL KIT. FURTHER INVESTIGATION FOUND THE PASSENGER WAS PLANNING TO VISIT THE HALEAKALA CRATER, AND ADVISED BY THE RANGERS THE LACK OF FIRE MATERIAL AVAILABLE NECESSARY FOR CAMPING. MR. S THEN PACKED THE MATCHES AND TISSUE PAPER, MATERIAL TO HELP CREATE A FIRE DURING HIS VISIT TO THE CRATER.     ALOHA AIRLINES TOOK SOME PHOTOS AND FORWARDED A REPORT TO THE LOCAL FAA OFFICIALS IN HONOLULU. PLEASE SEE THE ATTACHED PHOTOS AND REPORT SUBMITTED TO THE FAA.
column169: ALTHOUGH IT IS QUITE DIFFICULT TO ENSURE THE PASSENGER IS IN COMPLIANCE, THE TSA HAS BEEN ABLE TO DISCOVER NUMEROUS HIDDEN DANGEROUS GOODS IN A PASSENGER’S CHECKED OR CARRY ON BAGS. ALOHA AIRLINES AGENTS RECEIVE TRAINING ON POTENTIAL HIDDEN HAZARDOUS GOODS AND ISSUE BULLETINS TO INFORM OUR AGENTS TO BE VIGILANT IN IDENTIFYING THESE ARTICLES.
